 title: 'Embroidery File Formats Explained: DST, EXP, JEF, PES',
 description:
 'Embroidery machines read stitch files, not vector logos. DST is the universal commercial format. EXP, JEF, and PES are brand-specific. Here\'s what each format does, which machines use them, and how to know if your file is right.',
 category: 'How-To',
 readTime: '8 min read',
 date: 'May 9, 2026',
 isoDate: '2026-05-09',
 image: '/images/generated/service-embroidery.jpg',
 slug: 'embroidery-file-formats-explained',
}

const faqs = [
 { q: 'What is an embroidery file format?', a: 'An embroidery file is a machine-readable stitch sequence that tells an embroidery machine exactly where to put each stitch, in what order, what stitch type, what color, and where to trim. Unlike a vector logo (.ai, .eps, .svg) that describes shapes, an embroidery file describes physical stitches. The machine can\'t read a logo — it needs the stitch file.' },
 { q: 'What is DST?', a: 'DST (Tajima Data Stitch) is the universal commercial embroidery format. Created by Tajima for their commercial machines, it became the de facto industry standard. Almost every commercial embroidery machine — Tajima, Barudan, ZSK, Brother, Melco — reads DST. If your shop only sends one format, send DST.' },
 { q: 'What is EXP?', a: 'EXP (Melco Expanded) is the native format for Melco/Amaya commercial embroidery machines. It supports more advanced stitch information than DST including color stops and trims. Most Melco shops accept DST but produce slightly cleaner output from native EXP files.' },
 { q: 'What is JEF?', a: 'JEF (Janome Embroidery Format) is the native format for Janome home and semi-commercial machines. JEF files include color information that DST doesn\'t. If you\'re embroidering on a Janome MB-4, MB-7, or similar machine, JEF is the right format.' },
 { q: 'What is PES?', a: 'PES (Brother Embroidery System) is the native format for Brother and Babylock home embroidery machines. PES includes color and design information. PES files are the most common home-embroidery format on the consumer market — but commercial shops typically convert PES to DST for production.' },
 { q: 'Which file format should I send my embroidery shop?', a: 'DST is the safe answer — every commercial shop reads it. If your shop runs Melco machines, EXP produces marginally better output. If your shop runs Janome or Brother semi-commercial setups, JEF or PES respectively. Ask your shop directly: "What\'s your preferred file format?" and provide that.' },
 { q: 'Can I just send a JPG or PNG of my logo?', a: 'No — that\'s a logo, not a stitch file. The shop has to digitize it (convert it to a stitch file) before they can run it. Digitizing is a one-time service typically running $40-150 depending on logo complexity. After digitizing, the shop owns a DST/EXP/JEF/PES of your logo for all future orders.' },
 { q: 'Do I get to keep the digitized embroidery file?', a: 'Industry practice varies. Some shops include the file with the digitizing fee, some keep it as their working file. Best practice: ask upfront. If you change shops or want to embroider somewhere else, having the .DST file in hand saves $40-150 on re-digitizing. Get it in writing.' },
]

